<div class="line-numbers" aria-hidden="true" style="counter-reset:line-number 0"><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div></div></div><h3 id="how-to-use-responseentity" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#how-to-use-responseentity"><span>How to Use <code v-pre>ResponseEntity</code></span></a></h3>
<p>Basic structure: <code v-pre>ResponseEntity&lt;T&gt;</code>.</p>
<ol>
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity&lt;UserResponse&gt;</code></li>
</ol>
<p>Returns a full HTTP response, and the response body is a <code v-pre>UserResponse</code> object.</p>
<ol start="2">
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity.status(status).header(name, value).body(body)</code></li>
</ol>
<p>Use this when you want a specific status code, response header, and response body.</p>
<ol start="3">
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity.ok(body)</code></li>
</ol>
<p>Used for successful 200 <code v-pre>OK</code> responses.</p>
<ol start="4">
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity.noContent().build()</code></li>
</ol>
<p>Used when the operation succeeds but there is no response body. Very common for <code v-pre>DELETE</code>.</p>
<ol start="5">
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity.created(location).body(body)</code></li>
</ol>
<p>Used for <code v-pre>POST</code> creation.</p>
<ol start="6">
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(error)</code></li>
</ol>
<p>Used for <code v-pre>400</code> bad request.<br>
<strong>However, in real projects, prefer validation plus global exception handling.</strong></p>
<ol start="7">
<li><code v-pre>ResponseEntity.notFound().build()</code>:</li>
</ol>
<p>Used for <code v-pre>404</code> not found.<br>
<strong>In larger projects, it is often cleaner to throw a custom exception, and handle it globally.</strong></p>
<ol start="8">
<li>File download</li>
